03899nam a22005175i 9780774850292DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20072002xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807748502927 a10.59962/97807748502922doi  a(DE-B1597)661969  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aBV2815.N6 ǂb R87 2002eb 7aREL0450002bisacsh04a306.6/663711 aRutherdale, Myra, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWomen and the White Man's God :bGender and Race in the Canadian Mission Field /cMyra Rutherdale. 1aVancouver ;aToronto : bUniversity of British Columbia Press, c[2007] 4c©2002  a1 online resource (224 p.) :b32 b&w photos, 2 maps  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tBreaking Down the Barriers: Gender and the Anglican Church at Home -- tPerceptions and Interpretations of the “Other” -- t“I Wish the Men Were Half as Good”: Gender Relations in the Mission Field -- t“Oh, To Be in England”: Making a Home Away from Home -- tMotherhood and Morality -- tContesting Control while Encouraging Zeal -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBetween 1860 and 1940, Anglican missionaries were very active in northern British Columbia, Yukon, and the Northwest Territories. To date, histories of this mission work have largely focused on men, while the activities of women - either as missionary wives or as missionaries in their own right - have been seen as peripheral at best, if not completely overlooked. Based on diaries, letters, and mission correspondence, Women and the White Man's God is the first comprehensive examination of women's roles in northern domestic missions. The status of women in the Anglican Church, gender relations in the mission field, and encounters between Aboriginals and missionaries are carefully scrutinized. Arguing that the mission encounter challenged colonial hierarchies, Rutherdale expands our understanding of colonization at the intersection of gender, race, and religion. This book is a critical addition to scholarship in women's, Canadian, Native, and religious studies, and complements a growing body of literature on gender and empire in Canada and elsewhere.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aRELIGION / Christian Ministry / Missions.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia eBook-Package 2013-2000z978311141860540uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077485029240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774850292423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774850292/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  a978-3-11-141860-5  University of British Columbia eBook-Package 2013-2000c2013d2000  aGBV-deGruyter-alles